The Water Vapor Feedback\
\
The positive water vapor feedback is the most important atmospheric feedback in the climate system. Its existence was recognized over a century ago by Svante Arrhenius in the 1890s, though it took until the late 1960s and the first computer-based climate modeling work to understand its full significance. \
\
The water vapor feedback is fundamentally based on the principle that the atmosphere can hold exponentially more water vapor at higher temperatures. This is illustrated below, which is a plot of the \'91saturation vapor pressure of water\'92 as a function of temperature; equivalently, this figure shows how 100% relative humidity (or how air becomes completely saturated with water) changes with temperature.\
\
FIG: Vapor pressure: Saturation vapor pressure, \\(e^*\\) as a function of temperature and in units of hectopascals or hPa. Air in the real world can have less or sometimes slightly more water vapor than this, but if the water vapor concentration gets too much higher than this curve, the water will condense out into water droplets or snow.\
\
At the Earth\'92s globally averaged surface temperature of 288 K, the saturation vapor pressure increases by about 7% for a 1 K warming. Therefore the water vapor content of the atmosphere will increase by about 7% per K as the climate warms. Because water vapor is a powerful greenhouse gas, that is, it strongly absorbs and emits infrared radiation, an increase in the atmospheric water vapor content causes an increase in the downwelling infrared radiation at the Earth\'92s surface. This further increases the warming and thus the initial perturbation is amplified. So the water vapor feedback is a positive feedback.\
\
Surface evaporation can moisten a deep layer of air only if a mechanism exists to carry water vapor upward away from the surface. Turbulence of air currents near the surface helps, but isn\'92t enough to bring water vapor higher than 1 km.  Further lifting of moisture is necessary if the total moisture content of the atmosphere is to increase by very much. The most important mechanism for such further lifting is cumulus convection (see below). For this reason, convective clouds play an essential role in the water vapor feedback.\
\
FIG: cumulus convection. A picture of small and large cumulus clouds, formed by convection or rapidly rising moist air. The air around the cloud towers is slowly sinking. Some of the larger towers have flat cloud layers near their tops. These are regions where the air has stopped rising and is flowing out to the sides.\
\
The mass of water vapor in the atmosphere exceeds the mass of carbon dioxide by about a factor of 4, and water vapor contributes more to the downward infrared at the Earth\'92s surface than \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) does. Despite these facts, \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) plays a controlling role in the greenhouse effect, while water vapor plays a subservient role. The reason is that water vapor is condensible and can be removed from the atmosphere by precipitation, whereas \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) does not condense under conditions found in the Earth\'92s atmosphere.\
\
Lacis et al. (2010) illustrated the primary role of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) through a clever and simple experiment with a climate model. When run with realistic present-day \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) concentrations, the model produces a realistic simulation of today\'92s observed climate. In the experiment, Lacis and colleagues removed all of the \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) (and other noncondensing greenhouse gases) from the atmosphere. The results were spectacular. The surface temperature began to fall immediately as a direct result of the absence of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\). This led to a reduction in the water vapor content of the atmosphere and additional cooling through the water vapor feedback. The positive snow and ice albedo feedback also reinforced the cooling. The dramatic results are shown in the figure below. Within 10 simulated years, the Earth approached an ice-covered state in which the frigid model atmosphere contained very little water vapor.\
\
