\
Suppose that we ran a \'91mirror-image\'92 experiment, in which the \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) concentration was realistic but the water vapor content of the atmosphere was set to zero at the beginning of the simulation. Evaporation from the oceans would restore a realistic water vapor distribution within a few simulated weeks, and the simulated climate would stay close to what we observe today.\
\
An extreme version of the water vapor feedback, called the \'91runaway greenhouse\'92, likely occurred on Venus.(Ingersoll, \'91Planetary Climates\'92, (2013)) Venus is similarly sized compared to the Earth and very likely began its existence with a similar amount of water as the Earth. But Venus\'92 curse was that it was too close to the Sun and receives almost twice as much solar radiation as Earth (2601 \\(\\text\{W\}/\\text\{m\}^2\\) compared to Earth\'92s 1361 \\(\\text\{W\}/\\text\{m\}^2\\)). The extra solar radiation evaporated Venus\'92 oceans into its atmosphere, giving it a hot, moist, and dense water atmosphere. This would have increased the surface temperature so much that no life could survive. Water vapor that was high in Venus\'92 atmosphere could also be blown apart by high energy photons, allowing the hydrogen to escape to space. The oxygen then combined with other molecules at the surface and in the atmosphere so that eventually the hot Venus also lost its water. \
\
Current estimates suggest that it is unlikely that Earth will experience a runaway greenhouse due human activities (Ord probability here?). But if we manage to cause a mass extinction due to global warming, it will be through the water vapor feedback.\
