The Lapse-Rate Feedback\
\
Recall from Chapter 2 that the troposphere gets cooler with height. The rate that temperature decreases with altitude is called the atmospheric \'91lapse rate\'92. This can be described according to the equation \\(\\Gamma = - \\frac\{dT\}\{dz\} \\), where \\(T\\) is the temperature and \\(z\\) the altitude or height. The negative sign convention gives a positive number for \\(\\Gamma\\) in the troposphere. The global average lapse rate on Earth is about 6.5 K/km. \
\
As the atmosphere warms there are basically three different ways that the lapse rate could change in the troposphere. There could be a uniform warming shift, the lower part of the troposphere could warm more than the upper part, or the upper part of the troposphere could warm more than the lower part, see below.\
\
FIG: Lapse rate changes. Caption: Schematic of possible lapse rate changes in the troposphere due to global warming, based on a tropical lapse rate profile. The black line is the original, no-global-warming profile. The blue line shifts the profile uniformly while the purple and orange lines are shifts that favor the lower or upper troposphere.\
\
If the warming is uniform through the troposphere, as in the blue line above, then there is no strong lapse-rate feedback. But if the lower or upper troposphere is preferentially warmed, then there will be some interesting effects. Infrared photons that are emitted nearer to the surface have a harder time escaping to space because they are more likely to be absorbed somewhere in the atmosphere as they try to travel out to space. So a preferential warming of the surface, as in the purple line, ends up trapping more photons near the surface, which leads to more warming\'97a positive feedback. But if there\'92s preferential warming in the upper troposphere, as in the orange line, photons have an easier time escaping to space, meaning that a warming would lead to more efficient cooling\'97a negative feedback. Using terms we learned in Chapter 3 we could say that preferential warming near the surface decreases the atmosphere\'92s emissivity while preferential warming near the top increases the atmosphere\'92s emissivity.\
\
So under global warming, which of these occurs? The answer is actually all three: different regions on Earth have different lapse rate responses. But on a global average, the lapse rate response in the tropics ends up being much stronger than anywhere else, leading to an average preferential warming with height (as in the orange line above), and thus a negative feedback. \
\
Why do the tropics have a preferential warming with height? The tropics have a lot of rising moist air or moist convection, much more than anywhere else on Earth. And when the air rises and cools, eventually water will begin to condense out of the gas phase and into the liquid phase, thus forming clouds. But the transition from gas to liquid releases energy, called \'91latent heat\'92. Just the opposite process happens when you boil water: you have to add heat to transition the water from liquid to gas. So the atmosphere gets an additional boost of energy as the moist air rises and condenses into clouds. This leads to preferential warming with height and thus the tropics have a negative lapse rate feedback.\
\
Climate Sensitivity\
\
In this chapter we have discussed the four most important climate feedbacks: albedo, water vapor, lapse rate, and cloud. While there are other feedbacks, they are small compared to these four and don\'92t contribute significantly to the overall feedback of the climate system. With both positive and negative feedback processes in the climate system, it\'92s not clear at first glance what the overall response to global warming will be. For example, we saw that tropical convection could lead to both a negative lapse-rate feedback and also a positive high-cloud feedback. How do all of these combine and which are most important? \
\
To explore this, let\'92s return to the equations from the first part of this chapter. We found that a change in temperature due to a change in radiative forcing, accounting for feedbacks, could be described by the following equation,\
\
\\[\\Delta T = \\frac\{\\lambda \\Delta R\}\{1-f\} \\; .\\]\
\
We computed that a no-atmosphere planet would have a climate sensitivity parameter of \\(\\lambda = 0.27\\,\\text\{m\}^2\\text\{K\}/\\text\{W\}\\). For Earth with a realistic atmosphere, but with feedbacks turned off, it turns out that \\(\\lambda = 0.31\\,\\text\{m\}^2\\text\{K\}/\\text\{W\}\\). We know that the feedbacks \\(f\\) are going to have to be calculated based on the climate system. Though we should note that for a stable climate system \\(-\\infty < f < 1\\). But what value should we use for \\(\\Delta R\\), the change in radiative forcing? There have been many different radiative forcings that the Earth has experienced and because we don\'92t know for sure how humans will act in the future, we don\'92t know what the cumulative radiative forcing will be due to global warming once it is all done. A useful experimental framework that makes this easier and more unified is to use a \\(\\Delta R\\) that represents a doubling of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) from preindustrial levels. As you may recall from a previous assignment, the total radiative forcing from any doubling of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) in Earth\'92s atmosphere is approximately the same (e.g., from 10 ppm to 20 ppm or 400 ppm to 800 ppm). In a realistic Earth atmosphere this works out to be \\(\\Delta R = 4 \\text\{W\}/\\text\{m\}^2\\). \
\
The annual- and global-mean surface air temperature response to a doubling of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) is known as the \'91climate sensitivity\'92. Climate sensitivity is a central topic in the science of global warming. In fact many debates about global warming are often debates about the numeric value of Earth\'92s climate sensitivity because it is the theoretical concept that explains how much global warming we can expect to see. \
\
If there were no feedbacks, what would Earth\'92s climate sensitivity be (denoted as \\(\\Delta T_\{2xCO2\}\\))? With \\(f = 0\\) and using the values of \\(\\Delta R\\) and \\(\\lambda\\) above, we have that \\(\\Delta T_\{2xCO2\} = 1.24\\, K\\). What about if we add in the ice albedo feedback, \\(f_a\\)? The current best estimate(cite) of \\(f_a\\) is 0.09, so that works out to \\(\\Delta T_\{2xCO2\} = 1.36\\, K\\), for including only the albedo feedback. So the albedo feedback only increases the temperature by about 0.1 degree, which isn\'92t much. \
\
What if we put them all together? The total feedback factor is equal to the sum of the albedo, water vapor, lapse rate, and cloud feedback factors, so \\(f=f_a+f_w+f_\\Gamma+f_c=0.59\\), a value based on the most recent estimates(cite). The climate sensitivity including all these feedbacks comes out to \\(\\Delta T_\{2xCO2\} = 3.05\\, K\\). So a doubling of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) is estimated to result in about 3 degrees of global-mean warming. If we compare this value with the no-feedbacks case, we see that feedbacks amplify the warming and contribute about 2 degrees for a \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) doubling. This is a big difference. The global warming we\'92ve experienced thus far since the 1800s is about 1.3 K. If there were no climate feedbacks, keeping global warming in check would be much easier.\
\
A very important issue we\'92ve so far neglected in this discussion about climate sensitivity is the uncertainties involved. The calculations we\'92ve made here are for the average estimates of the radiative forcing, the climate sensitivity parameter, and the feedback factors. If you include the uncertainties in each, climate sensitivity is not a single value but actually a distribution of values. And then if you include different kinds of calculations, that can produce different distributions! One ambitious study set out to include as much information as reasonably possible to estimate climate sensitivity, see below. The main distribution to look at is the black \'91Baseline PDF\'92 plotted below. \
\
You can see that the most likely value of climate sensitivity is about 3 K. But the distribution spans a fairly wide range with the 5th to 95th percentile range being 2.3-4.7 K. Smaller values indicate a climate that is less sensitive to radiative forcing while higher values indicate a climate that is more sensitive. Note also that the distributions are \'91fat tail\'92 distributions: high values of climate sensitivity cannot be ruled out until about 7 K. \
